INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Is it hot?','熱いですか。','Atsui desu ka.',19,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Yeah, as for to me, it gets a little too hot, huh.  Use boku.  Use chotto.','ええ、ぼくにはちょっと熱すぎますね。','Ee, boku ni wa chotto atsusugimasu ne.',20,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Is that so.  Well, a little, let’s put in water.  Use sukoshi.','そうですか。じゃ、少し水を入れましょう。','Soo desu ka.  Ja, sukoshi mizu o iremashoo.',21,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('How is it, of about this much?','どうですか、このくらいで。','Doo desu ka, kono kurai de.  (gurai, also OK)',22,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Since, if we put in too much, it will become lukewarm.  Use to.  Plain speech.','入れすぎるとぬるくなるから。','Iresugiru to, nuruku naru kara. (nurui = tepid, lukewarm,  the nurse made Louie lukewarm tea)',23,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Let me see.  Still a little hot, but about this much hot, for the body is better, it appears, I have a feeling.  Use chotto.  Use kedo.  Use kono kurai.  Use hoo ga for the comparison.  Use yoo na to mean it appears.','そうですね。まだちょっと熱いけど、このくらい熱いほうが体にいいような気がします。','Soo desu ne.  Mada chotto atsui kedo, kono kurai atsui hoo ga, karada ni ii yoo na ki ga shimasu.  (ki ga suru = have a feeling that,  literally, feeling does)  (na shows that the preceding phrase modifies ki) (to say that an adjective or a verb seem to be, based on evidence, follow them with yoo or yoo na) (ki ga suru = to have a feeling that,  ki ni iru = it pleases me, ki ni iranai = I dislike,  ki ni suru = ki ni naru = worry about, be concerned,  ki ni shinai = to not care,  ki o otosu = to get downhearted,  ki o tsukeru = to be careful)',24,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Yeah, as for this place’s hot spring, it appears good to katakori and stomach’s sickness etc., for sure. Use ‘i’ to mean stomach.  Use rashii.','ええ、ここの温泉は肩こりや胃の病気にいいらしいですよ。','Ee, koko no onsen wa, katakori ya i no byooki ni ii rashii desu yo.  (kata = shoulder,  that kata [person] has big shoulders,  katakori = stiff shoulders,  there were stiff kata [shoulders]in Corinth from doing too much sculpture) (i = stomach,  there’s an eel in my stomach) (to state that a verb or adjective is true, based on hearsay, follow the verb or the adjective root with rashii) (byooki ni yoku kiku rashii, also OK)',25,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Katakori?  As for the one called katakori, what is it?  Use tte.','肩こり？肩こりって何ですか。','Katakori.  Katakori tte, nan desu ka.',26,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Ah, the shoulder muscle becomes hard and becomes painful thing it is for sure.  Use te to mean and.  Use koto.','あぁ、肩の筋肉が硬くなって痛くなることですよ。','Aa, kata no kinniku ga, katakunatte itakunaru koto desu yo.  (kinniku = muscle,  pro athletes have muscles of kin [gold] niku [meat]) cf. kinshi = prohibition) (katai = hard, firm, stiff, conscientious,  the cat eye, from the mouse’s perspective, is hard and firm) (not OK to substitute mono for koto, as katakori is a concept)',27,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('As for Michael, that kind of to-say thing (meaning, that sort of thing), doesn’t it exist?  Don’t use wa or ga after thing.  Meaning, doesn’t that happen to you?','マイケルさんはそういうことありませんか。','Maikeru san wa, soo iu koto arimasen ka.  (soo iu koto = that sort of thing)',28,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Yeah, it’s nothing, huh.  Meaning, it never happens.','えぇ、ないですねぇ。','Ee, nai desu nee.',29,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Another group’s person seems to be coming, huh.','他の団体の人が来たようですね。','Use the exclamatory tense.  Use yoo.Hoka no dantai no hito ga, kita yoo desu ne.  (dantai = group, party,  a group of dancing tigers)',30,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Gradually, shall we leave?   Use sorosoro.','そろそろ出ましょうか。','Sorosoro, demashoo ka.  (dandan not OK here,  OK to say dandan joozu ni natta = gradually I got skilled, or dandan futotta = gradually I got fat)',31,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Yeah, let’s do so.','えぇ、そうしましょう。','Ee, soo shimashoo.',32,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Ah, I drank well.  (meaning I had plenty to drink)  Plain speech.','ああ、よく飲んだ。','Aa, yoku nonda.',33,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('When you think about it, after you entered a hot spring, as for beer that one drinks, it’s delicious huh.  Use ato de.','やっぱり温泉に入った後で飲むビールはおいしいですねぇ。','Yappari, onsen ni haitta ato de nomu biiru wa oishii desu nee.  (ato ni nomu, also OK, not as good)',34,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Yeah, everyone seemed to be enjoying themselves, huh. Literally, it seemed pleasant. Don’t use wa or ga.  Use soo.','ええ、みんな楽しそうでしたね。','Ee, minna tanoshisoo deshita ne.  (tanoshikatta soo desu, not OK, as this means reportedly it was pleasant) (to state or exclaim how something appears to you, follow the stem of an i adjective, or a na adjective, or a verb stem, with soo, soo na, soo desu, or soo da)',35,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Stars, many are visible huh.','星がたくさん見えますね。','Hoshi ga takusan miemasu ne.  (if you substitute ooku for takusan, it sounds awkward,  you don’t say ooku no hoshi, but you can say ooku no hito)',36,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Tomorrow also the weather seems to be good huh.  Use soo.','明日も天気がよさそうですね。','Ashita mo tenki ga yosa soo desu ne. (instead of saying ‘isoo,’ say ‘yosa soo’,  yosa or nasa can precede soo, meaning ‘appears to be’,  e.g., mondai wa nasa soo da = it seems there isn’t a problem, kuruma wa yosa soo desu = it appears to be a good car,  cannot say kuruma soo desu) (yoi becomes yo, cannot say isa soo) (ii soo desu = someone said it was good,  yosa soo desu = it seems good,  mondai wa nai soo desu = someone said there is no problem,  mondai ja nasa soo desu = it appears it isn’t a problem,  oishisoo desu = it looks delicious,  oishii soo desu = reportedly it’s delicious,  kawaii soo desu = reportedly she’s cute,  kawaisoo desu = she’s pitiable, pitiful, poor)',37,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('That’s so, huh.  Ah, ah, ah-choo!','そうですね。はっ、はっ、ハックション。','Soo desu ne.  Ha, ha, hakkushon.   (when you hack into that cushion, the dust makes me say Ah-choo)',38,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Ah, Webb, it seems you caught a cold, huh.  Use yoo.','あ、ウエッブさん風邪を引いたようですね。','A, Uebbu-san, kaze o hiita yoo desu ne.',39,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Yeah, a little, a chill does.  (meaning I have a chill)  Use chotto.','えぇ、ちょっと寒気がします。','Ee, chotto samuke ga shimasu.  (samuke = chill,  a samui keg gives a chill when you drink from it)',40,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('Besides, a little fever also seems to exist.  Use sukoshi.  Use yoo.','それに少し熱もあるようです。','Sore ni, sukoshi netsu mo aru yoo desu.',41,27);
INSERT INTO JAPANESE_LESSON(english,japanese,romaji,exercise,lesson) VALUES('I’m sorry to hear that.  Plain speech.  Use an intensifier.','それはいけないな。','Sore wa ikenai na.',42,27);
